    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-16T05:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-16T05:29:00-05:00" n="160"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d160">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1616</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Moscow</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Summers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-16T13:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1918, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 18, 7 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>359. Your March 27, 7 p.m., and previous telegrams relating shoes. Runov states
                    Fabian already contracted for 1,000,000 pair shoes with
                        <persName>Endicott</persName> [<persName>Johnson</persName>, through?]
                        <persName>Sherman</persName>, and will possibly order 4,000,000 more at
                    price between 45 and 50 rubles delivered Moscow. … Moscow Supply Committee
                    supported by cooperative subordinates in surrounding governments which place
                    orders through it. They say they can get shoes mentioned in your March 27, 7
                    p.m., to members Cooperative Society and will give guaranties that same will not
                    fall into enemy’s hands. In case shipment is made I have to suggest that removal
                    from port be conditioned on future developments as situation very uncertain,
                    also suggest that Consulate General shall be consulted before distribution
                    made.</p>
                <p>The situation in Siberia and in central Russia should be watched carefully before
                    landing cargo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Summers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
